    _id: 'static-blog-13',
    title: 'How Are Schools Inspected in Dubai? A Guide to KHDA',
    slug: 'how-are-schools-inspected-in-dubai-khda-guide',
    excerpt: 'A complete guide to the KHDA school inspection process in Dubai — what inspectors look for, how schools are graded, and what the ratings mean.',
    author: 'Shamaila Shah',
    tags: ['KHDA', 'Dubai', 'Inspection', 'UAE'],
    isPublished: true,
    publishedAt: '2025-03-31T08:00:00.000Z',
    content: `<p>The Knowledge and Human Development Authority (KHDA) oversees the quality of private schools in Dubai and is responsible for conducting annual school inspections. For any school operating in Dubai, understanding the KHDA inspection framework is essential — not just for inspection day, but for guiding your school improvement strategy year-round.</p>
<h2>The KHDA Inspection Framework</h2>
<p>KHDA inspects schools across six key domains:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Students' Achievement</strong> — academic outcomes, progress, and standards</li>
  <li><strong>Students' Personal and Social Development, and Their Innovation Skills</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Teaching and Learning</strong> — quality of instruction, assessment, and feedback</li>
  <li><strong>Curriculum</strong> — breadth, balance, relevance, and continuity</li>
  <li><strong>The Protection, Care, Guidance and Support of Students</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Leadership and Management</strong> — including governance and self-evaluation</li>
</ol>
<h2>The Five-Point Rating Scale</h2>
<p>KHDA rates schools and individual domains on a five-point scale:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Outstanding</strong> — exceptional performance across all areas</li>
  <li><strong>Very Good</strong> — strong performance with only minor areas for development</li>
  <li><strong>Good</strong> — effective school with clear strengths and manageable areas for improvement</li>
  <li><strong>Acceptable</strong> — meets minimum requirements but with significant areas requiring development</li>
  <li><strong>Weak</strong> — below expectations; school requires urgent intervention</li>
</ul>
<h2>How Inspections Are Conducted</h2>
<p>KHDA inspections are typically unannounced or with very short notice. A team of trained inspectors visits the school for one to three days, conducting lesson observations, reviewing documentation, meeting with leaders and governors, speaking with students and parents, and analysing data. Their findings are compiled into a published inspection report available on the KHDA website.</p>
<h2>What Schools Should Focus On</h2>
<p>Consistently, the domains that most heavily influence the overall grade are Students' Achievement and Teaching and Learning. Schools that invest in classroom quality and data-driven improvement planning are the ones that move up the rating scale. KHDA also places increasing emphasis on innovation, student wellbeing, and inclusion — ensuring all students, including those with SEND, make strong progress.</p>`,
