    _id: 'static-blog-14',
    title: 'How Are Schools Inspected in Abu Dhabi? A Guide to ADEK',
    slug: 'how-are-schools-inspected-in-abu-dhabi-adek-guide',
    excerpt: 'Understanding the Abu Dhabi Department of Education and Knowledge inspection process is essential for every school leader in the emirate.',
    author: 'Shamaila Shah',
    tags: ['ADEK', 'Abu Dhabi', 'Inspection', 'UAE'],
    isPublished: true,
    publishedAt: '2025-04-07T08:00:00.000Z',
    content: `<p>The Abu Dhabi Department of Education and Knowledge — ADEK — is the regulatory authority for private schools in Abu Dhabi and Al Ain. It replaced the Abu Dhabi Education Council (ADEC) and has brought a refreshed inspection framework that schools operating in the emirate need to understand thoroughly.</p>
<h2>The ADEK Inspection Framework</h2>
<p>ADEK inspects schools across five core domains:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Students' Achievement</strong> — attainment, progress, and outcomes for different groups</li>
  <li><strong>Quality of Education</strong> — teaching, curriculum, and assessment</li>
  <li><strong>Students' Personal Development</strong> — behaviour, wellbeing, character, and UAE values</li>
  <li><strong>Leadership and Management</strong> — vision, self-evaluation, professional development, and governance</li>
  <li><strong>Students' Protection and Safeguarding</strong></li>
</ol>
<h2>ADEK's Rating Scale</h2>
<p>ADEK uses a four-point scale: Outstanding, Good, Acceptable, and Weak. Unlike KHDA's five-point scale, there is no "Very Good" category, which means the threshold for Outstanding is reached at a different relative standard. Schools should calibrate their internal evaluation accordingly.</p>
<h2>Key Differences from KHDA</h2>
<p>ADEK places particular emphasis on the UAE National Agenda and the integration of UAE culture, values, and history into the curriculum. Schools must demonstrate that students understand and can articulate UAE heritage and values, regardless of the curriculum they follow. ADEK also reviews Arabic language provision carefully, including for non-native Arabic speakers.</p>
<h2>Preparing Specifically for ADEK</h2>
<p>Beyond the standard quality assurance work, ADEK preparation should include: ensuring UAE Social Studies is delivered in accordance with Ministry of Education requirements, verifying that all students receive Arabic instruction appropriate to their level, and documenting evidence of UAE national events, cultural activities, and values education across the school year.</p>`,
